        0.6* youtube_trend
      + 0.30 * google_trend
      + 0.10 * novelty_score



PROBLEM 2 — Seed bank is too generic
--------------------------------------
Current seeds like "black holes", "roman empire", "volcanoes" have millions
of existing videos. Need discovery-level specificity.

CORRECT SOLUTION — Discovery database with novelty scoring:

Store each candidate as:
{
  "title": "...",
  "year": 2025,
  "source": "...",
  "novelty_score": 0-100
}

TWO-SIGNAL NOVELTY SCORE (replaces keyword-only approach):
- 30% lexical signal: match words like discovered/revealed/hidden/secret/ancient/
  impossible/mystery/unknown/lost/forbidden
- 70% recency signal: check Wikipedia API for recent page edits on the topic
  Endpoint: /w/api.php?action=query&list=recentchanges&rctitle={topic}
  Score: 100 if edited today, linear decay to 0 at 90+ days with no edits

NOTE: Pure keyword matching for novelty (originally proposed) is fragile.
"Secret Celebrity Diets" scores high but has zero factual novelty.
"Neutron star merger confirmed" scores low but is genuinely novel.
Recency signal from Wikipedia corrects this.

PROBLEM 3 — Saturation filter is wrong
----------------------------------------
Current: totalResults > 50000 -> reject
Problem: YouTube search count is a corpus size signal, not a competitive
density signal. "Black holes" has millions of results but is still viral.

CORRECT SOLUTION — View velocity of top results:

Fetch top 10 results:
  search.list?q={title}&type=video&order=relevance&maxResults=10

Retrieve statistics.viewCount per video. Compute median.

Decision thresholds:
  Median views < 100,000     -> PASS (low competition)
  Median views 100k-500k     -> PASS with -10 viral_score penalty
  Median views > 500,000     -> REJECT

